{"title_page": "Toy Matinee", "text_new": "{{Infobox album\n| name       = Toy Matinee\n| type       = [[Album]]\n| artist     = Toy Matinee\n| cover      = Toy_Matinee.jpg\n| alt        =\n| released   = 28 June 1990\n| recorded   =\n| venue      =\n| studio     =\n| genre      = [[Progressive rock]]\n| length     = 45:44\n| label      = [[Reprise Records|Reprise]]\n| producer   = [[Bill Bottrell]]\n| prev_title =\n| prev_year  =\n| next_title =\n| next_year  =\n}}\n{{Album ratings\n|rev1 = [[Allmusic]]\n|rev1score = {{Rating|3|5}}<ref>[{{Allmusic|class=album|id=r20369|pure_url=yes}} Allmusic review]</ref>\n}}<!-- Automatically generated by DASHBot-->\n'''Toy Matinee''' was a short-lived [[United States|American]] rock band, and also the title of their only album.  Their sound was an array of mixed influences, including [[progressive rock]], [[Album-oriented rock|AOR]] and [[Pop music|pop]] reminiscent of both the [[Beatles]] and the [[Beach Boys]].\n\nToy Matinee was formed by producer/composer/keyboardist [[Patrick Leonard]] in collaboration with singer/lyricist/multi-instrumentalist [[Kevin Gilbert (musician)|Kevin Gilbert]]. Backed by a group of session musicians (drummer [[Brian MacLeod (U.S. musician)|Brian MacLeod]], guitarist [[Tim Pierce]], and bassist [[Guy Pratt]]), and with guest appearances from several other musicians including [[Julian Lennon]], the duo recorded just one self-titled album which was released on [[Reprise Records]] in 1990.\n\nThe album was engineered and produced by [[Bill Bottrell]]. Thematically, it covered a rather broad ground.  Two tracks were dedicated to Czech poet and political figure [[V\u00e1clav Havel]] and painter [[Salvador Dal\u00ed]], while \"Queen of Misery\" is about [[Madonna (entertainer)|Madonna]].<ref>''[[Rolling Stone]]'', August 1991, \"[http://allaboutmadonna.com/madonna-interviews-articles/rolling-stone-june-13-1991 True Confessions: The Rolling Stone Interview With Madonna, Part One] {{Webarchive|url=https://archive.is/20130215114728/http://allaboutmadonna.com/madonna-interviews-articles/rolling-stone-june-13-1991 |date=2013-02-15 }}\" by [[Carrie Fisher]], in which Madonna says \"Pat Leonard, this guy that I write music with, wrote a song about me called 'Queen Of Misery.'\"</ref>  Leonard was the singer's longtime songwriting and producing partner, and in addition to him most members of Toy Matinee worked on Madonna's ''[[I'm Breathless]]'' album\u2014Gilbert as an engineer, Bottrell as producer and engineer, Pratt on bass, and Pierce on guitar.<ref>[http://www.discogs.com/Madonna-Im-Breathless/release/3799860 Discogs entry for \"I'm Breathless\"]</ref>\n\nAfter the album was released, session musicians Pratt, MacLeod and Pierce moved on to other work, and Leonard wasn't interested in a tour that involved replacing all of them.<ref>[http://www.kevingilbert.com/ricketts.htm Wayne Perez Interviews Brian MacLeod] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111113203333/http://www.kevingilbert.com/ricketts.htm |date=2011-11-13 }}</ref>  Gilbert took on that role himself instead, assembling a promotional band for the album which featured Gilbert's then girlfriend, [[Sheryl Crow]], on keyboards, [[Marc Bonilla]] on guitar. Spencer Campbell on bass. [[Toss Panos]] on drums. There were a number of short tours.\n\nA 1991 live recording of Gilbert and this touring band performing songs from the album was released in 2010 as ''Kevin Gilbert Performs Toy Matinee Live at the [[Roxy Theatre (West Hollywood)|Roxy]]''<ref>[https://popplusone.com/products/kevin-gilbert-performs-toy-matinee-live Kevin Gilbert Performs Toy Matinee Live]</ref>  The group engaged in heavy radio promotion wherever possible, most notably frequent appearances on the [[Mark & Brian]] show on [[Los Angeles]]-area station [[KLOS]].  Some of those sessions were released on Mark & Brian's KLOS compilation recordings,<ref>[http://www.kevingilbert.com/disco.htm Kevin Gilbert Discography] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130517160214/http://www.kevingilbert.com/disco.htm |date=2013-05-17 }}</ref> such as a stripped down version of \"The Ballad Of Jenny Ledge\" on their ''You Had to Be There'' collection.<ref>[https://archive.org/details/MarkAndBrian-CharityAlbums-YouHadToBeThere The Unofficial Mark and Brian Archive - Charity Albums - You Had To Be There (1997)]</ref>\n\nTwo of the songs on ''Toy Matinee'' -- \"The Ballad of Jenny Ledge\" and \"Last Plane Out\"\u2014received wide play on AOR stations partly due to Gilbert's promotional work, both of them peaking at No.&nbsp;23 on ''[[Billboard magazine|Billboard's]]'' Mainstream Rock Tracks chart.<ref>[http://www.allmusic.com/album/toy-matinee-mw0000308447/awards AllMusic Toy Matinee Awards]</ref> Despite the chart success of the singles, the album's highest U.S. chart position was No.&nbsp;129, and sales were below expectations enough that many unsold copies of the CD were widely available as [[Cut-out (recording industry)|cut-outs]] in the early '90s.\n\nGilbert went on to do additional work with Bottrell including Sheryl Crow's debut album and solo projects. In 1994, Leonard and former [[Mr. Mister]] [[Lead vocalist|frontman]] [[Richard Page (musician)|Richard Page]] released the album ''Meanwhile'' as [[Third Matinee]]. Gilbert's untimely death in 1996 ended any possibility of a second Toy Matinee album.\n\n== Personnel ==\n*[[Kevin Gilbert (musician)|Kevin Gilbert]] - vocals, guitar, keyboards\n*[[Patrick Leonard]] - keyboards, backing vocals\n;Session musicians\n*[[Brian MacLeod (U.S. musician)|Brian MacLeod]] - drums, percussion\n*[[Tim Pierce]] - guitar \n*[[Guy Pratt]] - bass\n*[[Bill Bottrell]] - guitar, percussion, backing vocals\n*Sal's Clarinet Trio: Jon Clarke, Jon Kip, Donald Markese - clarinet\n*[[Julian Lennon]] - backing vocals\n*[[Durga McBroom]] - backing vocals\n;Live band\n*[[Kevin Gilbert (musician)|Kevin Gilbert]] - vocals, guitars, keyboards, piano\n*[[Marc Bonilla]] - guitars, backing vocals\n*Spencer Campbell - bass, backing vocals\n*[[Sheryl Crow]] - keyboards, piano, backing vocals\n*[[Toss Panos]] - drums, percussion\n\n== Album track listing ==\n{{Track listing\n| all_writing = Patrick Leonard and Kevin Gilbert, except where noted\n\n| title1      = Last Plane Out\n| writer1     = Leonard, Gilbert, Guy Pratt\n| length1     = 5:12\n\n| title2      = Turn It On Salvador\n| note2       = dedicated to [[Salvador Dal\u00ed]] 1904-1989\n| writer2     = Leonard, Gilbert, Pratt\n| length2     = 4:55\n\n| title3      = Things She Said\n| writer3     = Leonard, Gilbert, Pratt\n| length3     = 4:58\n\n| title4      = Remember My Name\n| note4       = for [[V\u00e1clav Havel]]\n| writer4     = Leonard, Gilbert, Bill Bottrell\n| length4     = 5:16\n\n| title5      = The Toy Matinee\n| writer5     = Leonard, Gilbert, Pratt\n| length5     = 5:02\n\n| title6      = Queen of Misery\n| length6     = 4:30\n\n| title7      = The Ballad of Jenny Ledge\n| length7     = 5:49\n\n| title8      = There Was a Little Boy\n| length8     = 5:33\n\n| title9      = We Always Come Home\n| writer9     = Leonard\n| length9     = 4:29\n\n| total_length = 45:44\n}}\n\n{{Track listing\n| collapsed = yes\n| headline = 2001 Special Edition additional tracks / 2008 reissue bonus tracks\n\n| title10  = eenitaM yoT ehT\n| length10 = 0:33\n\n| title11  = Blank Page\n| writer11 = Gilbert\n| length11 = 2:23\n\n| title12  = Things She Said\n| note12   = Alternate Version\n| length12 = 5:13\n\n| title13  = There Was a Little Boy\n| note13   = Early Version\n| length13 = 4:15\n\n| title14  = Last Plane Out\n| note14   = Early Version\n| writer14 = Leonard, Gilbert, Pratt\n| length14 = 5:35\n\n| total_length = 63:43\n}}\n\n=== Surround Releases ===\n\nIn 1999 the album was remixed into surround by DTS Entertainment, released as a [[DTS (sound system)|DTS]] encoded [[5.1 Music Disc|5.1 compact disc]] with a slightly altered version of first track \"Last Plane Out\".<ref>[http://soundstage.com/music/reviews/grev029.htm SoundStage Review - Toy Matinee (DTS CD)]</ref>  A second DTS version was released in 2001 as a [[DVD-Audio]] title, using [[Meridian Lossless Packing]] and a 2.0 channel stereo version of the album encoded in [[Dolby Digital]].<ref>[http://www.audioholics.com/music-reviews/toy-matinee-dvd-a-dts-review Audioholics Toy Matinee DVD-A/DTS Review]</ref>  The 2001 stereo remaster and the 2.0 Dolby Digital version on the DVD-Audio release all include the alternate \"Last Plane Out\".  None of the bonus tracks were included on either surround release.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.bluedesert.dk/toymatinee.html Toy Matinee page at Blue Desert]\n* [http://www.kevingilbert.com Official Kevin Gilbert website]\n* [http://myspace.com/toymatinee Unofficial Myspace Page]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:American progressive rock groups]]\n[[Category:1990 debut albums]]\n[[Category:Albums produced by Bill Bottrell]]\n[[Category:Reprise Records albums]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox album\n| name       = Toy Matinee\n| type       = [[Album]]\n| artist     = Toy Matinee\n| cover      = Toy_Matinee.jpg\n| alt        =\n| released   = 28 June 1990\n| recorded   =\n| venue      =\n| studio     =\n| genre      = [[Progressive rock]]\n| length     = 48:45\n| label      = [[Reprise Records|Reprise]]\n| producer   = [[Bill Bottrell]]\n| prev_title =\n| prev_year  =\n| next_title =\n| next_year  =\n}}\n{{Album ratings\n|rev1 = [[Allmusic]]\n|rev1score = {{Rating|3|5}}<ref>[{{Allmusic|class=album|id=r20369|pure_url=yes}} Allmusic review]</ref>\n}}<!-- Automatically generated by DASHBot-->\n'''Toy Matinee''' was a short-lived [[United States|American]] rock band, and also the title of their only album.  Their sound was an array of mixed influences, including [[progressive rock]], [[Album-oriented rock|AOR]] and [[Pop music|pop]] reminiscent of both the [[Beatles]] and the [[Beach Boys]].\n\nToy Matinee was formed by produc